","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Trollope","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Troughburn in Hethpool (Northumberland), which was formerly known as <i>Trollop</i>. The old placename appears to derive from Old Norse <i>troll</i> ‘troll, supernatural being’ + Old English <i>hop</i> ‘small enclosed valley’.","History: An English family of this name trace their descent from John Trowlope, who lived at Thornlaw (Durham) in the late 14th century. One of his descendants was the novelist Anthony Trollope (1815–82)."],"variants":[{"name":"Tulip","meanings":["English (Northumberland and Durham): probably a late variant of   Trollope  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":2,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":12,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William de Trollope was born in 1094, in Doddington, Lincolnshire, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth Coleby de Trollope. He died after 1173, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1094–Aft 1173":"1094–pärast 1173","1060–Female":"1060–Surnud","1122–1161":"1122–1161","1094–1173":"1094–1173","1106":"1106","1122":"1122","Aft 1173":"pärast 1173","1096":"1096","1173":"1173","1161":"1161","1094":"1094","1060":"1060","Doddington, Lincolnshire, , England":"Doddington, Lincolnshire, England","Doddington, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Doddington, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1094–Aft 1173":"1094–1173 jälkeen","1060–Female":"1060–Kuollut","1122–1161":"1122–1161","1094–1173":"1094–1173","1106":"1106","1122":"1122","Aft 1173":"1173 jälkeen","1096":"1096","1173":"1173","1161":"1161","1094":"1094","1060":"1060","Doddington, Lincolnshire, , England":"Doddington, Lincolnshire, England","Doddington, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Doddington, Lincolnshire, Englan